Answer:
When a student discloses they are being abused at home, a staff member must take the following actions:

*   Let the pupil know that they must pass the information on, as staff are not allowed to keep secrets [1.13].
*   During the conversation with the pupil, the staff member must:
    *   Allow them to speak freely [1.13].
    *   Remain calm and not overreact [1.13].
    *   Give reassuring nods or words of comfort, such as "I'm so sorry this has happened," "I want to help," "This isn't your fault," or "You are doing the right thing in talking to me" [1.13].
    *   Not be afraid of silences [1.13].
    *   Under no circumstances ask investigative questions, but it is reasonable to ask clarifying questions to support a meaningful referral (e.g., when did this happen, where did this happen) [1.13].
    *   At an appropriate time, tell the pupil that the information must be passed on in order to help them [1.13].
    *   Not automatically offer any physical touch as comfort [1.13].
    *   Avoid admonishing the child for not disclosing earlier [1.13].
    *   Tell the pupil what will happen next [1.13].
    *   Let them know that someone (either the staff member or another named person, such as the Designated Safeguarding Lead) will come to see them before the end of the day [1.13].
*   Report verbally to the Designated Safeguarding Lead (DSL) [1.13].
*   Seek support if they feel distressed or need to debrief [1.13].
*   All staff have an equal responsibility to act on any suspicion or disclosure that may suggest a child is at risk of harm at home [1.3].
*   It is the responsibility of staff to report their concerns; it is not their responsibility to investigate or decide whether a child has been abused [1.11]. They must report all concerns, however minor or insignificant, as they do not need 'absolute proof' that the child is at risk [1.11].
*   When concerned about the welfare of a child, staff members should always act in the interests of the child [1.3].

